    <text id="B1093T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Phelps' states that he considers both Frederick Tukey and George Cook to be good
                    officers.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>

        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="statement" id="d5">
                

                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1867-02-07"><abbr expan="February">Feb.</abbr> 7<hi
                                rend="underline">
                                <hi rend="super">th</hi>
                        </hi> 1867</date>
                        <name type="place">Staunton Va</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute/>
                </opener>

                <p>I am acquainted with F. S. Tukey <abbr expan="Esquire">Esq</abbr>
                    <abbr expan="Assistant Superintendent">Asst. Supt.</abbr> of the Freedmens
                    Bureau, and it is my judgement that he is well qualified for the office, and I
                    would not hesitate to recommend him most cordially for such position. I came to
                    Staunton last March, and have personally known Mr Tukey for some months. I must
                    also <unclear>bear</unclear> my testimony to the <unclear>officering</unclear>
                    of <abbr expan="Lieutenant">Lt.</abbr> Cook who lately filled the same position
                    in this place. I esteem both the gentlemen named and so far as I know they are
                    both good officers.</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute/>
                    <signed>E.P. Phelps P.E.<lb/>Rockingham District<lb/>Baltimore
                            Conference<lb/><abbr expan="Methodist Episcopal">M.E.</abbr>
                    Church</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
